I"Ü!<h2 id="enable-site-wide-settings-using-jekyll-and-sass">Enable site-wide settings using Jekyll and Sass</h2>

<p><em>This tutorial works really well for Jekyll sites hosted onÂ <a href="https://cloudcannon.com/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">CloudCannon CMS</a></em>.</p>

<h3 id="overview">Overview</h3>

<p>Thanks to <a href="https://lilybruns.com">Lily Bruns</a> to encouraging me to learn this! Hereâ€™s the background storyâ€¦</p>

<p>Lily asked me to implement aÂ <strong>structure that allows editors to easily change basic settings on their CloudCannon site</strong>, like colors, fonts, logos, etc without having to fiddle with code files. The projects are hosted onÂ <a href="https://cloudcannon.com/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"><strong>CloudCannon</strong></a>, a CMS for Jekyll which is quite awesome. The objective was toÂ <em>allow editors to use the CMSâ€™s UI for intuitive changes</em>Â of these settings, without having to go to a _config.yml file or similar.</p>

<p>After some preliminary analysis Iâ€™ve opted to work with Sass instead of CSS Variables as it is much more powerful for this set up. With that said, it will still work with plain CSS Variables.</p>

<h3 id="before-we-start">Before we startâ€¦</h3>

<p>Please note that this process breakdownÂ <strong>assumes familiarity with Sass</strong>; FreeCodeCamp has thisÂ <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_a5j7KoflTs" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">great tutorial</a>Â that covers some of the basic functions (donâ€™t be scared by the 2hr-length: focus on the first half hour for a good insight on how Sass works).</p>

<h3 id="set-up--folder-structure">Set-up &amp; Folder Structure</h3>

<ol>
  <li>First, letâ€™s install a Sass/SCSS processor on our code editor (Atom, etc.). This will ensure that <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">scss</code> files are processed into <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">css</code> when we save them.</li>
  <li>Next, letâ€™s set up our folder structure as usual; letâ€™s also add some markup to our <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">index.html</code> file for reference.</li>
  <li>Then, we create a <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">main.scss</code> file and place it on our styles folder: this is ourÂ <strong>main</strong>Â scss file which Jekyll will render.</li>
  <li>We can create a <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">_sass</code> folder and include all ourÂ <strong>Sass partials</strong>, mixins and all here (the Sass â€˜@importâ€™ partials).</li>
  <li>Next, we create a <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">_data</code>Â <strong><em>folder</em></strong>Â and create a <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">settings.yml</code>Â <strong><em>file</em></strong>Â inside of it: this is where we will put all the variable values for Jekyll to output from Liquid tags.</li>
</ol>

<h3 id="implementation-jekyllfy-sass">Implementation (â€œJekyllfy Sassâ€)</h3>

<h4 id="configuring-your-settingsyml-file">Configuring your <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">settings.yml</code> file</h4>

<p>We should set up the structure &amp; values of our variables here. Colors, font embed codes, images, etcâ€¦ Anything we want to have on the CloudCannon user interface. This will allow CloudCannon to display these keys in a user-friendly interface on their Explore view. They have a nice database of keys which are displayed with their own UI, which we can refer toÂ <a href="https://docs.cloudcannon.com/editing/interfaces/inputs/" rel="nofollow">here</a>. As an example:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>general_settings:
  site_title: My awesome site
  site_url: 'https://example.com'
  preview_image:
  social:
    - icon: "LinkedIn"
      url: 'https://linkedin.com/'
    - icon: "Github"
      url: 'https://github.com/'
theme:
  heading_font_family: '"Glegoo", serif;'
  body_font_family: '"Bitter", serif;'
  dark_color: '#222'
  light_color: '#d2d2d2'
  accent_color: '#1fc71f'
seo:
  description_text:
  fb_app_id:
  keywords: []
configuration:
  head_code_block: '
    &lt;link rel="stylesheet" href="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/gridlex/2.7.1/gridlex.min.css"&gt;
    &lt;link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com"&gt;
    &lt;link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Bitter:ital,wght@0,200;0,300;0,400;0,700;1,200;1,300;1,400&amp;family=Glegoo:wght@400;700&amp;display=swap" rel="stylesheet"&gt;'
  body_code_block:
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Note that some of these keys haveÂ <strong><em>underscore</em></strong>Â rather than aÂ <em>dash</em>; this syntax allows CloudCannon to read the keys and provide the friendly UI for editors, so definitelyÂ <a href="https://docs.cloudcannon.com/editing/interfaces/inputs/" rel="nofollow">check their documentation</a>Â for more detailed information.</p>

<h4 id="configuring-the-mainscss-file">Configuring the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">main.scss</code> file</h4>

<p>The <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">main.scss</code> file needs to have empty Front Matter for Jekyll to process it;Â <strong>we do so by adding 2 lines of 3 dashes <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">(â€”--)</code> at the top of the file</strong>. So:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>
---
---
// Write your SCSS from here onwards

</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Write our <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">scss</code> normally, and where weâ€™d normally place the value for the Sass variables (that is, in our <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">main.scss</code> stylesheet), we place a Liquid tag to pass the values from the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">settings.yml</code> file. Following this projectâ€™s example,Â <em>in our <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">main.scss</code> file</em>, instead of:</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">$dark_color: '#222';</code></p>

<p>we should set:</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">$primary_color: {{site.data.settings.theme.dark_color}};</code></p>

<h3 id="overall-the-mainscss-file-should-look-something-like-this">Overall, the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">main.scss</code> file should look something like this:</h3>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>
---
---
// note the 2 lines of dashes with empty front matter above: that's what tell Jekyll to process this file
// describe your Sass variables BEFORE you add partials that take these values (like universal styles) otherwise Jekyll will throw an error as it cannot parse the information for the partials

$dark_color:  {{site.data.settings.colors.primary_color}};
$light_color: {{site.data.settings.colors.secondary_color}};

// write your SCSS from here, for example:

h1 {
  color: $dark_color;
}
body {
  background-color: $light_color;
}

// or a better alternative, add partials from the _sass folder to render the stylesheet:

@import
  '_resets',
  '_typography';

</code></pre></div></div>

<h4 id="important-settings-for-_configyml-when-using-scss-partials">IMPORTANT: settings for <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">_config.yml</code> when using scss partials</h4>

<p>In case we are using partials, we must add the following code to our <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">_config.yml</code> file:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>
sass:
  sass_dir: _sass
  
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>NB:Â <em>This is the path for the directory storing the scss partials; we can configure it to suit our project structure.</em></p>

